          <msContents>
            <summary>Manuscript used for recitation and contemplation, is a poetic treatment of Sanskrit poetics, literary aesthetics, and rhetoric (alaṃkāraśāstra); title translates as Bouquet of rasa, a reference to a nectar-like flavor or essence correlating to a heightened aesthetic awareness for the hearer of the poem; text uses sexual imagery such as different types of illicit women referred to as nāyikās. Manuscript praises the Hindu deity Pāṇḍuraṅga, a regional deity from Maharashtra linked to the child Kṛṣṇa (f. 22v).</summary>
            <textLang mainLang="san">In Sanskrit</textLang>
            <msItem>
              <title>Rasamañjarī</title>
              <title type="vernacular">रसमञ्जरी</title>
              <author>
                <persName type="authority">Bhānudatta Miśra</persName>
              </author>
              <respStmt>
                <resp>scribe</resp>
                <persName type="authority">Gaurīśvara</persName>
              </respStmt>
              <colophon>Colophon: iti śrīmadbhānudattaprākāśetārasamaṃjarīsamāptaḥ // śāke maheśamihikāṃśukalāprayukte jyeṣṭhetuṣārakara ekakalāvaśeṣe // śrībhānuva[ca]racitārasamaṃjarīyaṃ gaurīśvareṇa likhitādharaṇījavāre sarasvatyai namaḥ // śubhaṃm astu // śrīpāṃḍuraṃgāropaṇam astu // (f. 22v).</colophon>
            </msItem>
